12209,PullRequestEvent,2018-03-01 17:25:41+00:00,91020334,ni/nimi-python,11483903,texasaggie97,5598284.0,ni,169507871,,"Create ""Fancy Fetch"" for niscope",closed,False,742,"- [X] This contribution adheres to [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/ni/nimi-python/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md).
- [X] I've updated [CHANGELOG.md](https://github.com/ni/nimi-python/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md) if applicable.
- [X] I've added tests applicable for this pull request
### What does this Pull Request accomplish?
* Change `fetch()` to be more user friendly
  * `fetch(timeout=5.0, num_samples=None, fetch_relative_to=None, fetch_offet=None, fetch_record_number=None, fetch_num_records=None, wfm=None)`
  * `fetch_relative_to`, `fetch_offet`, `fetch_record_number`, & `fetch_num_records`: If not `None` will set the corresponding attribute
  * If wfm is not `None` calls the appropriate `fetch_into()` function
  * In Python 3, a memoryview of each record is created and added to the corresponding `wfm_info`
  * In Python 2, an array.array is created and the points are copied.  `memoryview` in Python 2 only supports string and bytearray, not array.array or numpy.ndarray of arbitrary types. :(
* Additional documentation requires #722 
* Instead of returning all of the captured data in a single 1D array that the user has to then correlate different parts to each record, the waveform for a given record is put into the corresponding wfm_info
  before:
  ``` python
  # Assume num records = 2
  wfm, wfm_info = session.channel[[0,1]].fetch(num_samples=1000)
  # Channel 0, record 0
  # wfm_info[0].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm[0:999]
  # Channel 1, record 0
  # wfm_info[1].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm[1000:1999]
  # Channel 0, record 1
  # wfm_info[2].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm[2000:2999]
  # Channel 1, record 1
  # wfm_info[3].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm[3000:3999]
  ```
  after:
  ``` python
  wfm_info = session.channel[[0,1]].fetch(num_samples=1000, fetch_num_records=2)
  # Channel 0, record 0
  # wfm_info[0].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm_info[0].wfm
  # Channel 1, record 0
  # wfm_info[1].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm_info[1].wfm
  # Channel 0, record 1
  # wfm_info[2].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm_info[1].wfm
  # Channel 1, record 1
  # wfm_info[3].<absoluteX, etc.> and wfm_info[1].wfm
  # Basically, the waveform becomes just one more attribute on the waveform info object
  ```

