12719,PullRequestEvent,2017-01-17 22:25:22+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,12059307,electronwill,6392739.0,conda,101960080,,fix changelog typos,open,False,4347,fix changelog typos,https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/issues/4347,,,2017-01-17T22:25:22Z,1,4,4,1,[],[],[],[],,,,,[],https://github.com/conda/conda/pull/4347.patch,https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/pulls/4347/commits,010,['e4254f8bc2601f90afef385ac4cc8962c57c950a']
12761,PullRequestEvent,2018-02-02 15:48:26+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,151929,minrk,6392739.0,conda,166835177,,import installers before invoking any,open,False,6834,"avoids removing parts of conda_env before they are imported, since conda_env itself may be changed or deleted, e.g. by upgrading Python or conda itself.

closes #6824

I was able to test this with this Dockerfile:

```dockerfile
FROM continuumio/miniconda3:4.3.27
RUN conda install -y conda=4.4.8
RUN conda info
RUN conda list
COPY test.yml test.yml
ADD conda_env /conda/conda_env
RUN cp /conda/conda_env/cli/main_update.py /opt/conda/lib/python3.6/site-packages/conda_env/cli/main_update.py
RUN conda env update -n root -f test.yml
```

and this test.yml

```yaml
dependencies:
  - python=3.5
  - pip=9
  - pip:
    - wheel
```",https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/issues/6834,,,2018-02-02T15:48:26Z,1,12,4,1,CONTRIBUTOR,[],[],[],,,,,[],https://github.com/conda/conda/pull/6834.patch,https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/pulls/6834/commits,010,['f2e176b203e91de79917af47bd0937f643755a2b']
12766,PullRequestEvent,2015-08-12 09:32:34+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1882046,Korijn,6392739.0,conda,42220430,,Add option --create_env to conda install command,open,False,1518,"In continuous integration scenarios I currently resort to the following boilerplate to ensure that a conda environment is used:

```
conda create --yes --quiet --name <env> --file requirements.txt
conda install --yes --quiet --name <env> --file requirements.txt
call activate <env>
<interesting actions here>
call deactivate <env>
```

Obviously, after the first run, the `conda create` call will always throw an error.

This PR makes it possible to avoid the boilerplate, by creating the environment if it does not exist yet in the `conda install` command:

`conda install --yes --quiet --name <env> --file requirements.txt --create-env`",https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/issues/1518,,,2015-08-12T09:32:33Z,1,9,4,2,[],[],[],[],,,,,[],https://github.com/conda/conda/pull/1518.patch,https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/pulls/1518/commits,010,"['ba61e87923dbc541b1460d3b9ded8454beff6148', '2bde01a2124ab324ecd4d2b358d5c6515dacfa1d', '22b782c9209852ef126b1d041195c7db9debac71']"
