16690,PullRequestEvent,2018-02-23 23:27:37+00:00,55101236,googleapis/artman,25311427,vam-google,16785467.0,googleapis,171140555,,ArtmanFlow initial commit,open,False,396,"1) To start web-mode (highly recommended option): `python artmanflow/web/index.py`, then go to `http://127.0.0.1:5000/` in your browser.
2) To run individual step manually in a docker (using source generation step as example):
   2.1) Edit (optional) `artmanflow/web/templates/sources_generation.yaml`
   2.2) Run `python artmanflow/steps/sources_generation_host.py artmanflow/web/templates/sources_generation.yaml`
3) To run individual step on local machine (not in docker), using source generation step as example:
   3.1) Edit (note all the paths in the config should be local machine-specific) `artmanflow/web/templates/sources_generation.yaml`
   3.2) Run 'python artmanflow/steps/sources_generation_guest.py artmanflow/web/templates/sources_generation.yaml

In case of the option (1) the overall usage of the tool should be intuitive, if no, please let me know.

In case if the ""Debug Mode"" is selected on execution, the tool will copy internal docker relevant files (like corresponding cheked out/modified repos) in the `/tmp` directory of the host machine. With this option, one can troubleshoot generation process and/or do manual edits of the generated stuff. For example, on the staging step, to do some modifications in posted PR and push an 'amendment' commit without need to checkout the branch separately: just go to the `/tmp/java-src-stage-<execution_id>/guest_output/guest_root_dir_snapshot`, the checked out repo will be there, avaliable for manual modifications if requried.The link to the actual `/tmp/java-src-stage-<execution_id>` is provided at the top of the exectution output page for each step.

The overall tool structure is as follows:
- `artmanflow/steps` contains `*_host.py` and `*_guest.py` scripts for each implemented step. The host script prepares environment and then runs the guest script in docker. The guest script is the script which does the actual work. Both scripts can be run individually in ""standalone"" mode, for guest scripts linux environment is assumed.
- The `artmanflow/web` directory contains files to support running the stuff from web-ui.
- The web-ui tries to organize the whole process in a form of a workflow.
- Each ""step"" in the workflow implements some reasonably big self-contained chunk of work. The steps are separated by mandatory (for our process as we have it now) ""approval"" (i.e. manual) steps (like approve automatically generated PR).
